column1: How many Battery Electric Vehicles (BEVs) will be registered in the UK in 2022, according to the Society of Motor Manufacturers and Traders (SMMT)?
column5: ['Fewer than 150,000', 'Between 150,000 and 200,000, inclusive', 'More than 200,000 but fewer than 250,000', 'Between 250,000 and 300,000, inclusive', 'More than 300,000 but fewer than 350,000', '350,000 or more']
column6: ['Business', 'Technology', 'Environment']
Looks like final total will just reach above 250k. I have expected around 240k for a long time, so I am making a late attempt to correct this.
this question was devised to find the leaker
adjusting a bit having thought about it.

Having to adjust based on the updated figures for October, which shows a gain in total volume of 26.4% - outside the range I had expected. BEV market share was very close at 14.8% but the total number of BEVs was proportionally higher than forecast at approx 20k. On that basis the following two months could lead to total volume similar to 2021 (1.647M) and BEV share just over 15% for a final tally approx 250k - right on the break point.
Re-evaluating slightly higher based on expecting a slight increase in BEV supply for the final Qt and Tesla adding to December figures.

September figures are just out: 38.1K BEVs added, totalling 175.6k YtD. I'd estimated up to 38k on 5th September including a tranche of Teslas (their Model 3 added approx 6.9k on it's own) which are bulk registered on entry to the UK. September is historically the most active month with a new plate, hence the higher figures than previous few months. Also of note is the market share for September at 16.9%, and YtD 14.5%, which confirms to me that the annual share should be no more than 15.5% given there is 1Qt to go, Tesla increased the share for September, other macro factors are only changing slowly (other than inflationary), and pent-up demand should lessen any reduction in sales caused by inflation and other rising costs of living. Overall volume was up 4.6%, but YtD down 8.2%. On that basis I'd expect total volume circa 91-94% of 2021 and ~15.5% market share = 225-240k. Combining this view with an anticipated volume of 40-60K for the final Qt using a forecast trend in comparison with last year, I get a total 215-235k, and a consensus at around 225-235k. Forecast unchanged.

The UK is sinking into recession given soaring fuel prices and inflation. IMHO, Liz Truss's announcement of tax cuts for the rich won't help BEV sales as middle-class customers are being hammered financially.
137,498 ytd (End of August?)

August figures are just out at 10K BEVs (and 14.5% market share), within the 10-12K estimated a month ago. No big change to forecast. Things could change in September with Tesla registrations added, and this could push up market share but >250k looks out of reach.Overall BEVs at around 15% of the total market still looks right, with the total market down 6-10% from last year. Total 228k +- 20K.
Following @alh given https://www.gjopen.com/comments/1489910
Allowing a little more latitude for Tesla

Revising downwards as bin 4 looks unrealistic given that the economic forecast in the UK is not looking like it will improve, as well as the lack of political will to increase adoption (charging networks, incentives/subsidies as prices increase, both PM candidates being unenthusiastic about any kind of green revolution), which will likely offset any increase in production.
Interesting update for July figures: 12,243 BEVs and 10.9% market share (from 112,162 total).
115k to june or 19k/month

I'm expecting 16-21k BEVs for July, based on historic trends combined with ongoing economic and manufacturing issues as cited previously. Outside this range I may have to reconsider, but til then the data and trend for me points towards an additional ~120-150k units over next six months , producing a total range of 235-265k.
Small adjustment after useful comments with @alh
Anything outside the range 230-275k is looking implausible to me, based on previous rationales and half year figures.
Reaffirming forecast
June figures now out: BEV 16.1% on total sales down 24.3% YoY. Total BEV for half-year 115k.Year to date market share 14.4% on total sales down 11.9%.

I seem to be off from the crowd on this one - a range outside 225-280k looks unlikely to me, based on a number of previous rationales. The figures for June will be interesting; I’m expecting the half year totals to show market share at ~14% on total sales down ~8.9%, and will adjust based on the new data.

I still can't see how 300k+ is achievable unless the outlook dramatically changes; currently fleet sales are down 26% YoY and overall sales -8.7%. Given market conditions and continuing devastation in Ukraine, combined with the other known factors affecting manufacturing and supply, even a late surge towards the end of year would perhaps bring total volumes similar to 2021 (I'm expecting June to be similar to May, giving half-year totals as -8% and BEV share 14%).
I was previously big on the last two bins (esp. bin 5), but the cost of living crisis seems to be hitting hard and isn't being managed at all in the UK.
I'm still not quite convinced that all the known issues will be resolved fully through 2022 to produce both a increase in YoY sales, and BEV share more than 15%.

While 300k+ looks less feasible in current market conditions and supply-chain issues, it would only take a small uptick in BEV sales through the second half of the year to clear 250k. I'm adjusting towards bin 4 being the most likely, and staying with an expected range around this level at roughly 250-315k.
Staying mostly on bin5 but switching from bin 6 to bin 4 as my "second choice" to accommodate overall economic outlooks for the year.

April figures are out, showing BEVs taking a 10.8% monthly share on total sales down 15.8%. YtD BEV now at 14.4%, a decline from the first Qtr (15.4%). Given foreseen inflationary pressures and other economic and manufacturing issues I’m edging overall sales down, and expecting BEV share to stabilise circa 14.5-16%. While supply chain issues may ease in Q3 and Q4 household spending is likely to tighten significantly, and recent sales have been higher in the private sector than fleet.

March figures show overall sales down by 14.3% but BEV taking a 16.1% share. Year to date: BEVs at 15.4% market share from total sales –1.9%. Forecast from March 4th still roughly holds up: https://www.gjopen.com/comments/1409207
https://www.smmt.co.uk/2022/04/new-car-market-feels-supply-chain-squeeze-during-critical-new-numberplate-month/

Auto sales will be impacted for the remainder of the year as chip supplies worsen because of the war. At the same time the soaring gas prices will aid in the shift towards electric. https://www.cnbctv18.com/technology/russia-ukraine-crisis-may-worsen-global-chip-shortage-12663432.htm https://www.nbcnews.com/business/autos/will-high-gas-prices-supercharge-electric-vehicle-sales-rcna18444 On the whole my estimate remains largely unchanged moving slightly towards the crowd

It's still early in the year, but January and February have both shown strong sales increases from 12 months ago. But at 27.5% and 15% growth respectively there is clearly a lot of volatility based on continuing issues with supply-chains and chip shortages, while the BEV share increased to 17.7% of market. Overall demand should stay strong relative to production, so I am still in line with original forecast with overall sales up on 2021 and BEV increasing market share. The harder part is how much ground will the BEV market take this year and whether global tensions will impact sales. Approx 15-20% growth overall still looks very achievable, and the BEV market share looks fairly locked in at 13-14%, with potential up to perhaps 18% due to buyers 'future proofing' after a long wait, along with manufacturers prioritising BEVs (partly due top margins and industry shift) and steady shift in marketing and media attention towards sustainability, climate issues etc. So as a base level: 1.647M vehicles last year * 1.15/1.20 = 1.894/1.976M total BEV share 14-18% gives a low range of 265-340k and a more likely upper range of 276-355k so far.
February data has been released. https://www.smmt.co.uk/vehicle-data/car-registrations/
BEV registrations are much more likely to increase than decrease -- redistributing my lower bound probability estimate to the upper bound.

The data available from SMMT for free is: - Monthly new car registrations broken down by Diesel, Petrol, and AFV (this figure adds up MHEV, PHEV, HEV, and BEV). - Granular fuel type breakdowns (including BEV as its own segment) for January 2022 and January 2021 only. Given this data I think a suitable modelling approach would be: - Estimate the total number of car registrations in 2022 - Estimate the % of car registrations that are AFV (alternative fuel vehicles) - Estimate the % of AFV vehicles that are BEV (battery electric vehicles) -- this assumes that people choosing alternative fuel vehicles choose between the range of options.
Oil prices looking like they might be up for a while makes BEVs more attractive.

January sales were up, so I continue to use higher total vehicle sales (1.8 vs 1.6 for 22 vs 21 allowing for some of the uplift in January to be pandemic driven). The shares of BEV is lower in January than recent months (12.75 vs 25%), this maybe due to supply chain issues - there are long waiting lists. One months data can have a lot of noise but I am adjusting for a more balanced forecast until trends change.

January 2022 shows a massive increase in new BEVs compared to January 2021, including in the market share (6.9% -> 12.5%, https://www.smmt.co.uk/vehicle-data/car-registrations). There's still some way to go with economic issues, potentially a new variant, and so on, but this seems to favour bins 5/6 quite clearly.

BEVs just for November 2021 were about 21,000, or 252,000 annualized. With supply chain issues sand semi conductor shortages expected to lessen later this year, both the new cars total and the share of BEVs will continue to grow.

Have kept a reasonably high bin 3 due to a couple of months of Omicron impact. All the factories will have no staff, supply chains will have no staff, dealers no staff. Should be able to rule it out in a couple of months Apart from that I agree with other forecasts

Another 76.3% increase would mean ~336k. Total market seems relatively steady and largest growth seems to be BEV in most markets. As "Britain’s ratio of plug-in vehicles on the road to standard public chargers (16:1) was one of the worst among the top 10 global electric vehicle markets at the end of 2020." that could either mean a lot of potential growth as the market is surging in spite of lack of infrastructure, or that the lack of infrastructure could now start to hamper growth.
Expecting 275 - 320k. Still in line with original forecast, but its early days yet: https://www.gjopen.com/comments/1368060
Following @DNK89 because of (1) excellent attention to the base rate https://www.gjopen.com/comments/1368097 (2) Outstanding ratio of Brier to median of 0.757.

The growth of electric cars in the UK is climbing high. According to "Inside EVs", as of May '21 there were 13,120 BEVs registered in the UK, which was up 441% year-over-year. As stated above, "as of November 2021, 163,022 Battery Electric Vehicles were registered in the UK in 2021". That's already huge growth just between May and November. Given growing concern about climate change, here is no reason to believe that the growth will decline.
revised basic assumption for 2021 overall count
Doubles on average every year last few years. Return to average and return to new normal after COVID should increase overall car registration. On negative side chip crisis.

Opening Estimate Based on a crude calculation 21726*12 = 260712 (If Nov monthly volumes were sustained for the next year). This represents a floor to the possible values, should ideally be higher than this) Have to look up plans for upcoming capacity for BEVs and factor in other manufacturing issues. Will refine my estimate when i find the time

Quite a few factors to tackle: current supply chain issues, chip shortages, pressure on metals supply (particularly aluminium/magnesium) and other rare earth materials, and other pandemic omicron-related issues will all affect the next quarter, holding back growth. But the trend towards NEVs will continue to increase as new models are released from a wider range of manufacturers, tech improvements increase battery range, prices become more competitive, and infrastructure is developed further. Charging stations are now more widespread, particularly across Europe where growth is over 30% YoY, although Government spend is reducing compared to market as a whole. Overall the BEV market looks certain to increase through the year, as will market share.

Normally UK registrations are 2.3, but have fallen to 1.6 post pandemic. Conversely the share of BEV is rising and is recently (Nov 21, 25% of new registrations). I assume the most likely scenario is a recovery in volumes in 2022 (as supply chain issues recede) and a continuing share of BEV's at close to current levels. For example two plausible scenarios 1.8 new reg and 25% BEV = 450. A stronger recovery back to 2.3 but a lower BEV share of 15% = 345. That makes me think around 350 is likely and biased toward the upside.

SMMT expects that sales for 2022 are going to exceed the combined sales for the previous decade (https://www.smmt.co.uk/reports/smmt-business-plan-2021/). The annualized sales for BEV in 2021 are 167K and I assume a 100% growth rate per year for the past decade (https://www.smmt.co.uk/vehicle-data/evs-and-afvs-registrations/ || https://www.nextgreencar.com/electric-cars/statistics/). The result of the combined sales for the last decades is 333K. So I would assume at this point to be the expected sales for 2022. Further I assume a tight distribution distribution around that value of potential sales for 2022.

It’s no secret that more countries are pushing toward cleaner energy. However price range and tax can put a snag on sales increase. If car makers find ways to make bev more affordable as we begin to come out of the pandemic we can definitely see a huge jump of sales
Somewhere near double the 2021 value, given fast current growth. 5-10% of new registrations

Looking at the data, there was an 88.9% increase from 2020 to 2021. The same increase in 2022 would result in 307949 BEV vehicles registered in 2022. I think the increase will be at least this big as (i) incentives to buy a BEV vehicle are increasing as we get closer to even hybrids being phased out, (ii) increase in the available supply of BEV vehicles from multiple manufacturers, (iii) improvements in the charging grid make traveling outside of town with a BEV more realistic. Moreover, the numbers for 2020 and 2021 represent data for years where car sales were every previous year except for 2008 so as we (hopefully!) get further out of the pandemic, the overall number of registered vehicles could go up quite a bit, with the share of BEV going up as well.
